inscription.text: At 10.15 first tendency to assume a cup-form at sides, a truncated cone appearing in the centre. Fig 96
Grea agitation and swaying of the protoplasm. Fig 97
At 10.18 an edge of thin protoplasm is becoming more and more apparent. Will this develop cilia? Fix 98.
At 10.20 separation more complete. The vesicles are longer and thinner. Fig. 99
At 10.22 cilia now developed from the belt spoken of above. Fig. 100
There is no tendency to assimilation at present. Will this come with the completion of the cilia? Fig. 101
At 10.27 a curious occurance in b voricella. A ridge of cilia (?) appears at a. Fig. 102
10.45 the lower belt of cilia on b at a appear very active. Do they assist in the final division of the stalk, and why to do they not appear in c? Fig 103
At 11.5 division complete as far as cells go. The stalk is at present common property. Fig. 104
At 11.35 the stem was completely separate and then left microscope. Fig 105
At 10.15 first tendency to assume a cup-form at sides, a truncated cone appearing in the centre. Fig 96
Grea agitation and swaying of the protoplasm. Fig 97
At 10.18 an edge of thin protoplasm is becoming more and more apparent. Will this develop cilia? Fix 98.
At 10.20 separation more complete. The vesicles are longer and thinner. Fig. 99
At 10.22 cilia now developed from the belt spoken of above. Fig. 100
There is no tendency to assimilation at present. Will this come with the completion of the cilia? Fig. 101
At 10.27 a curious occurance in b voricella. A ridge of cilia (?) appears at a. Fig. 102
10.45 the lower belt of cilia on b at a appear very active. Do they assist in the final division of the stalk, and why to do they not appear in c? Fig 103
At 11.5 division complete as far as cells go. The stalk is at present common property. Fig. 104
At 11.35 the stem was completely separate and then left microscope. Fig 105
